  "text": "The Firefox Content Security Policy (CSP) enforcement infrastructure in dom/security/ is organized around several core components:\n\n1. **CSP Parsing**: The nsCSPParser class (dom/security/nsCSPParser.cpp and .h) implements the complete CSP directive parsing logic. The static method parseContentSecurityPolicy() is the main entry point that tokenizes a CSP policy string and builds an nsCSPPolicy object following the W3C CSP specification.\n\n2. **CSP Context and Policies**: The nsCSPContext class (dom/security/nsCSPContext.cpp and .h) implements the nsIContentSecurityPolicy XPCOM interface and manages the collection of CSP policies for a document. It contains the core policy evaluation logic through methods like permitsInternal() for general permission checking and GetAllowsInline() specifically for inline script and style evaluation.\n\n3. **Inline Script Evaluation**: The critical method for script-src evaluation of inline scripts is nsCSPContext::GetAllowsInline() (dom/security/nsCSPContext.cpp, starting around line 637). This method handles script-src-elem, script-src-attr, style-src-elem, and style-src-attr directives, implementing the W3C spec's matching algorithm including checks for nonce, hash, unsafe-hashes, and strict-dynamic.\n\n4. **CSP Utilities and Violation Reporting**: The nsCSPUtils namespace (dom/security/nsCSPUtils.cpp and .h) provides utility functions for CSP logging and enforcement, including CSP_LogLocalizedStr() and CSP_LogMessage() for console messages. The CSPViolationData struct (dom/security/CSPViolationData.cpp and .h) encapsulates information about CSP violations including the blocked content source, effective directive, line numbers, and code samples.\n\n5. **XPCOM Interface**: The nsIContentSecurityPolicy interface (dom/interfaces/security/nsIContentSecurityPolicy.idl) defines the public XPCOM interface for CSP interaction, including CSPDirective enums for all supported directives (DEFAULT_SRC, SCRIPT_SRC, SCRIPT_SRC_ELEM, SCRIPT_SRC_ATTR, etc.) and methods like GetAllowsInline() for inline content evaluation.\n\n6. **Violation Reporting**: The nsCSPContext::ReportInlineViolation() method and related functions in nsCSPUtils handle reporting violations through SecurityPolicyViolationEvent, logging to console, and sending violation reports to report-uri/report-to endpoints.\n\nThe inline script evaluation flow follows the W3C spec: when a script or style element is encountered, GetAllowsInline() checks policies in order, verifying that either (a) inline behavior is allowed via 'unsafe-inline', (b) a valid nonce attribute matches the policy, (c) the content hash matches a hash-source in the policy, or (d) for scripts, the 'strict-dynamic' keyword allows parser-created scripts. If none match, a violation is reported and the content is blocked (unless report-only mode)."
}

